  "faq_items": [
    {
      "q": "What color is Copper Canyon, really?",
      "a": "A warm, anchored brown with visible reddish or amber granule accents. In direct Florida sun it reads as a clear sienna or coffee; in shade it softens to a near-black. The blend is layered enough that the surface looks alive rather than flat."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does Copper Canyon pair with red brick?",
      "a": "Yes, and that is the canonical pairing. Brown asphalt and red brick share a warm tonal family, so they read as one coordinated elevation rather than competing colors. The trick is keeping the trim color clean and bright (warm white, soft cream) so the eye has somewhere to rest."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does Copper Canyon fade over time?",
      "a": "Minimally. GAF's ceramic granule coating holds warm tones for 25 plus years in Florida UV. Browns tend to drift slightly cooler over the first 5 years (a barely visible shift) and then stabilize. The full warranty covers premature fading. Source: GAF product warranty card and NRCA Asphalt Shingle Manual."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will Copper Canyon make my house run hotter?",
      "a": "Slightly. Dark warm tones absorb similar solar heat to dark grays, adding roughly 5 to 10 degrees Fahrenheit to peak-summer attic temperatures versus a light gray. Proper ventilation and a radiant barrier under the decking keep monthly cooling-cost impact under 20 dollars in most homes."
    },
    {
      "q": "How does Copper Canyon compare to other browns in the asphalt category?",
      "a": "The 'brown' SKUs across major brands sit within a fairly tight tonal window. Most are mid-to-dark brown with warm undertones; differences are mostly in granule blend size and shadow-line depth. Use the Compare tab to see direct hex deltas against similar SKUs."
    },
    {
      "q": "Is brown a 'dated' roof choice?",
      "a": "On a contemporary white-stucco build, possibly. On a craftsman, traditional, Tudor, or Mediterranean elevation it is the most architecturally correct choice and reads as deliberate rather than dated. Picking by house style matters more than by trend."
    }
  ],
